3.1 Responsibilities and Accountability for Emergency Response Planning.  

The organization’s program documentation should clearly articulate responsibilities and accountability for this function. For example, at large sites, an individual (perhaps a member of the safety and security staff) might be assigned overall responsibility for the preparation of the facility emergency response plan and be assisted by a team assembled from different areas of the facility. During plan preparation, the team leader or his designate would act as liaison with the various off-site groups (e.g., other industrial facilities and public agencies near the facility).  Assistance from knowledgeable personnel at such facilities and agencies ensures the availability of needed information, builds communication channels and trust between mutually dependent parties and, thus, can help ensure cohesion of the program.

Smaller organizations or facilities may require external assistance when developing the plan; however, the responsibility for the plan and its application remains with the facility. The responsible person should ensure that the plan is periodically audited and updated, as required. Considerations that might prompt the need for updating the plan include:

•	changes in the nature or magnitude of process hazards;
•	significant changes in organization (either within the facility or in an external organization) that may affect emergency response capabilities;
•	changes in communication systems (including phone numbers and radio frequencies);
•	changes in external population distributions;
•	changes in regulatory requirements; and
•	recommendations made because of an audit, incident, or exercise.


