ractices in place, incidents may still occur. Whenever hazardous chemicals are handled, some risk of an incident remains, despite well-engineered equipment, detailed operating procedures and highly trained personnel. Should an incident occur, such as an explosion or a release into the environment, its effects may be localized to the immediate vicinity or the effects may extend off-site, depending on the magnitude of the incident. An understanding of possible incident scenarios, their potential effects and, perhaps, their likelihood, serves as the basis for rational emergency response planning.  Proper planning allows the facility to prepare for dealing with both the incident and its effects. These plans may involve dedicated, specialized equipment or facilities, detailed procedures and specialized training of personnel. Clear, thorough documentation is critical to this effort.

1.2.	Goals and Benefits

The goals of the emergency response program are:
•	to minimize the impacts of an incident (including health effects, costs, legal implications, loss of corporate image, and deterioration of relationships with employees and with the public);	
•	to identify aspects of other programs that affect emergency preparedness, and to address these in a practical way; and
•	to participate in a cooperative effort with the public, i.e., the local community, through the Local Emergency Planning Committee (LEPC) and other appropriate agencies and officials.

A wide range of benefits can result from effectively documenting an emergency response program, especially when it involves the local community and authorities. These include:

•	the speed and efficiency of response in an emergency can be significantly improved, bringing lower risk to employees and members of the community;
•	relations between industry and the community can be improved by the implementation of a sound, well documented and well-publicized emergency response program;
