Audit Scope. Within the context of the documentation task, the audit should be focused on verification that a documentation program exists and that it is being followed as described. For example, in auditing Process Hazard Analysis (PHA), the team should first check that the program for implementing PHA defines the documentation requirements for PHA. The team should next check that the records produced when implementing PHA are documented in a manner that complies with the requirements of the program.  It should be remembered that, when auditing PSM documentation, the intent is not to confirm the technical accuracy or the merit of the contents of the documentation. Rather, the intent is to confirm that the documentation practices conform to the established program requirements. Auditing may, however, reveal areas of potential improvement in the implementation of the PSM element itself. Such findings, while beyond the scope of the documentation audit, could be separately documented and forwarded to the responsible parties for consideration. 

Audit Frequency. The frequency of audits will vary, as dictated by the needs of the organization or facility, or per regulatory requirements. In defining a schedule for audits, consideration should also be given to:
•	degree of risk in the facility;
•	seriousness of findings in the last audit;
•	age of the installation;
•	interval since the last audit;
•	extent of changes since the last audit; and,
•	incident history since the last audit.

