3.	Audit Documentation

3.1.	Audit Program Documentation

Organizations implementing an audit program should include in their PSM program documentation a discussion of the goals of auditing as well as any general procedures required for implementation of the function. Such program guidance would generally address the following items:

Audit Program Responsibility. Functional responsibility and accountability for the audit function should be clearly defined in the program documentation.

Audit Team Composition. Since there are a wide variety of PSM systems in place, independent teams with appropriate qualifications should perform these auditing functions on behalf of management. The number and experience of those conducting the audit will vary per the unique circumstances of the activity being audited. Auditing techniques need to be learned and practiced, and organizations may wish to consider establishing minimum standards of
training for those individuals filling key roles on the audit team. Audit team leaders are typically personnel independent from the systems being audited. Generally, one member of the team should be responsible for the collection of the various inputs to the audit and for recording the audit. Where complex technology is involved, an expert in the technology is needed, at least as an advisor. Smaller audits may be performed by only one person; however, auditors could benefit from the assistance of an independent person or persons to cover the following topics:
•	chemistry;
•	process engineering;
•	maintenance;
•	operations;
•	safety (fire protection, electrical, materials handling); and,
•	auditing (technique).

