2.2.	Types of Audits

The objectives of the various audits can be different, and sometimes require different approaches. Three principal types are briefly described in the following paragraphs.

MAI Systems Audit. This type of audit consists of a careful review of the systems involved in the management of the PSM elements. Basically, it is a confirmation check that procedures and practices exist. Verification activities should include checking to see than
•	documentation is adequate and used effectively (a sampling approach may be necessary);
•	resources (personnel and otherwise) are sufficient;
•	audit schedules are being met; and responses to problems are timely.

Process Safety Audits. This audit type is generally more detailed and specific than a PSM systems audit. Process safety audits seek to verify that the actual practices are in accordance with established procedures. Each PSM element may have a specific audit procedure or focus. For large facilities, it may be necessary to divide the documentation system into more manageable parts to ensure comprehensive coverage of the various PSM elements and their documentation. Sampling for verification is an important aspect of performing audits. In addition, efforts should be concentrated on areas subject to change. This includes both documented change involving change request and authorization forms and hard-to-recognize incremental changes that may occur in a facility over long periods of time.

