3.	Description of Process Equipment Integrity

a.	Objectives
i.	The main objectives in establishing a documentation system for process equipment integrity are:
1.	Provide procedures to ensure that key safety aspects of equipment design, fabrication, installation, and operation have been considered;
2.	Provide data to allow safe, efficient equipment operation; and
3.	Furnish adequate information to support equipment maintenance or modification throughout its useful life.
b.	Process Equipment Integrity as Part of Process Safety Management
i.	The Process Equipment Integrity elements ensures that consideration of equipment reliability and suitability for safe performance of function is addressed throughout the following phases of the equipment life cycle:
1.	Equipment definition and categorization;
2.	Equipment design and/or selection;
3.	Procurement;
4.	Fabrication, initial inspection and testing;
5.	Equipment installation;
6.	Initial start-up;
7.	Useful service life;
8.	Maintenance, repair, modification, and replacement;
9.	Testing and inspection during life cycle;
10.	Use in training; and
11.	Other special tasks such as, decommissioning, demolition and removal
ii.	Maintaining up-to-date and accurate data for equipment is an important element of any facility process safety management (PSM) effort. Typically, the amount of PSM related equipment information grows as an equipment item progresses through its life cycle. The phases above are presented are in chronological order and each phase requires, to some degree, the information generated in earlier phases for its safe, successful completion. The generation, compilation, and protection of this information, so that it is available to the appropriate personnel, should be addressed for each phase of the equipment life cycle.
